      "writtenOn": "2021-01-14T02:00:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "but what if there are two different text/plain encodings, and the user wants a specific one. If we ignore everything after \";\", then the client would be getting not what they asked for.\n\nWhy not keep it dead simple for now? i.e. exact match",
      "parentUuid": "9b4ab437_d99f3b57",
      "revId": "34f7e25a721735c9f30a7d0645abceabbba755cf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b62b28c5_b1d976dc",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/v1/predicate.proto",
        "patchSetId": 8
      },
      "lineNbr": 118,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000487
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-14T14:45:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Fine to keep it simple.\n\nThe reason I bring this up is that I think the service should preemptively deny text formats that are not UTF-8. This reduces the complexity of the system, we can assume much more.\n\nSo anything that is text/plain, text/html, application/json, application/xml, text/xml, etc so be required to be UTF-8. For example with json, it\u0027s encoded as \"application/json; charset\u003dutf-8\". The problem is that each mime type has a different way to specify the encoding, and the way to specify it is a bit open ended, e.g. this is likely valid \"text/plain;    encoding\u003dUTF-8   \".\n\nAnyhow, it\u0027s a separate topic and not that much a big deal. My main fear is that this field won\u0027t work well in practice and when we realize it\u0027ll be a bit late and organically grown.",
      "parentUuid": "d03e63bf_bc3ab39c",
      "revId": "34f7e25a721735c9f30a7d0645abceabbba755cf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "18f4d86c_b6032359",
        "filename": "resultdb/proto/v1/predicate.proto",
        "patchSetId": 8
      },
      "lineNbr": 118,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-14T21:57:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i see your point.\nit seems a bit orthogonal to BQ Exports. I think this is more about when the data flows into ResultDB, as opposed to when it send it to BQ (at that point, it is kind of already too late).\n\nGTest has a case when they unintentionally produce incorrect UTF-8 sequence due to a bug. Developers still need to see what was produced, and download that, so we cannot reject that data.\n\nThoughts?",
      "parentUuid": "b62b28c5_b1d976dc",
      "revId": "34f7e25a721735c9f30a7d0645abceabbba755cf",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
